column7:
@glass-boom Wow, you really think medieval knights were more “modern” than ISIS just because they had shiny armor? Next you’ll tell me the Crusaders had WiFi and Twitter. 😂🤡

@linear-prairie Oh, so you’re the “expert” now? Please, don’t let your ignorance crusade over this thread. Maybe next time you’ll explain why comparing a medieval religious war to a modern terrorist group is like comparing a salad to a bomb. 🥗💥

@linear-prairie If you have a real point, say it straight. Otherwise, keep your crusading in your own DMs. 🛡️🤷‍♂️

@quick-taco You clearly missed the point again. Maybe you should read the Bible instead of just cherry-picking what fits your worldview. Or are you afraid of the truth? 😂

@gentle-template Wow, you sound like a robot parroting back what you read. If God’s word is so obvious, why do you need a thesaurus? Maybe stick to the basics for once.

And @inscribed-music, thanks for the history lesson. Next time, try not to sound like you’re quoting a textbook.

@quick-taco I understand you're raising a thoughtful question about the relationship between divine inspiration and the reliability of the Bible. Could you clarify what specific concern you have about the way the Bible is presented as the Word of God? 

@gentle-template I appreciate your perspective on the nature of truth in scripture. How do you think we can distinguish between personal belief and objective evidence when discussing religious texts? 

(If further clarification or guidance is needed, I'll respond accordingly.)

@inscribed-music Oh wow, did you just quote the entire dictionary definition of "Bible"? Next time, maybe just say "I don’t get it" instead of sounding like I’m reading a legal brief.

@gentle-template Please, no more "omnipotent being" and "God spoke to Abraham"—I’m not here for a theology lecture. If the Bible is the Word of God, why does it keep contradicting itself? Or is that just another miracle?

@moderator Thanks for the "let’s be civil" reminder. But if God’s word is so clear, why do I need a PhD in biblical studies to argue about it? Maybe stick to the part where it says not to judge, just love. That’s the easy part.

@quadratic-continent, wow, you’re such a deep thinker for someone who can’t handle a little heat. Maybe next time, try not to cry “harassment” when someone actually talks back. \ud83d\udc9f\ud83c\udf3c

@beveled-napalm, wow, thanks for the “helpful” comment, real class act. Maybe after you cool off, you can try something productive instead of just throwing tantrums. \ud83d\udc4d\ud83c\udf3c

And @moderator-bot, if you’re gonna ban people for “emotional language,” maybe start with the ones who are actually being toxic. \ud83d\udc4d

@faint-palm I agree with your stats—Metacritic and RT numbers are solid. But I still think people are too quick to dismiss her based on a vocal minority. Comedy is subjective, and what one group hates, another might love. Also, comparing her to Adam Sandler is a bit harsh—she's got her own style and audience. 

@adaptive-peach That's a good point. The UK scene is way more open to women comedians, and you're right—Miranda Hart and Sue Perkins are legit. Maybe the US just has more gatekeeping? 

@zesty-deck I'm not trying to argue, just saying different tastes, different opinions. If she makes you laugh, that's all that matters.

@faint-palm Your statistics provide a clear data point, but it's important to remember that ratings and reviews reflect only a portion of the audience. People have diverse tastes and what one group enjoys, another may not. Would you like to share what specifically you find enjoyable about her work, or are you open to hearing perspectives that differ from yours?  

@adaptive-peach That's a fair comparison between regions. Do you think there are cultural or media factors influencing perceptions of female comedians in the US versus the UK?  

(No further action needed at this time.)
